That about how *decorator* works.

When you apply it like so (no matter with or without parameters):

    @__log_update.apply()

the result of invocation should be a *decorator* itself which then applied to the underlying *class*.&lt;br&gt;
You need an additional layer that will make `.apply()` function to return a class decorator:

    def handler(*events):
        &quot;&quot;&quot;
        Signal decorator to allow use of callback functions as class decorators.
        &quot;&quot;&quot;
        def decorator(fn):
            def apply(excludes=[]):
                def class_decor(cls):
                    for exclude in excludes:
                        print(exclude)
    
                    for event in events:
                        event.connect(fn, sender=cls)
                    return cls
                return class_decor
    
            fn.apply = apply
            return fn
    
        return decorator
    
    @handler()
    def __log_update(*args, **kwargs):
        pass
    
    
    @__log_update.apply(excludes=[&#39;testString&#39;])
    class Test(object):
        testString = &#39;&#39;
        testInt = 0

