answers.body_markdown:
Don&#39;t make your controller function a suspend function. They can only be called from other suspend function or coroutines.

I don&#39;t know exactly how your endpoint gets built without errors, but since it is executed - there is **no coroutine context inside - because we didn&#39;t define any**! Thats why you get a NPE for the context.

BTW: The code below will have no asyncronous behaviour, because you await immediately - just like normal sequential code:

    async {
        doSomething()
    }.await()

---

To fix your problem fast, here how I would rewrite it:

    @GET
    @Path(&quot;/test&quot;)
    fun test() : String {
        GlobalScope.launch { // Starts &quot;fire-and-forget&quot; coroutine
           doSomething() // It will execute this in separate coroutine 
        }
        return &quot;Hello&quot; // will be returned almost immediately 
    }



To understand more about context, read [this][1]. **TLDR**: Use Kotlin&#39;s builders and functions to create a context - like `runBlocking`

---

**EDIT**

To avoid `GlobalScope.` functions, we can use `runBlocking`

    @GET
    @Path(&quot;/test&quot;)
    fun test() : String = runBlocking {
        val deferredResult1 = async { doSomething() } // Starts immediately in separate coroutine
        val deferredResult2 = async { doSomethingElse() } // Starts immediately in separate coroutine

        logger.print(&quot;We got:${deferredResult1 .await()} and ${deferredResult2 .await()}&quot;)
        
        &quot;Hello&quot; // return value - when both async coroutines finished
    }


  [1]: https://kotlinlang.org/docs/reference/coroutines/coroutine-context-and-dispatchers.html

